üëâ All runtime exceptions extend RuntimeException.

üö® 6. Errors (not exceptions, but runtime)

StackOverflowError

OutOfMemoryError

VirtualMachineError

AssertionError

These cannot be handled normally.


. Exception Keywords

    try	        Block containing risky code
    catch	    Handles the exception
    finally	    Always executes
    throw	    Throw an exception explicitly
    throws	    Used in method signature to declare checked exceptions
    rethrow	    Throw the same exception again



CASE 1: int x = 0; (String) x
‚ùå This does NOT compile at all.

Because primitive types (int, boolean, char, etc.) cannot be cast to reference types (String, Object, etc.).

‚úî Type of error ‚Üí Compile-time error (NOT an exception)

Exact error message (similar to):

inconvertible types: int cannot be converted to String


‚ö†Ô∏è Since the program never runs, no exception occurs, only a compile-time TYPE error.


CASE 2: Object x = 0; (String) x
This compiles because:

0 autoboxes to Integer

So Object x = 0; ‚Üí Object x = new Integer(0);

Compiler thinks: maybe this can be a String, so it allows the cast.

BUT at runtime, Integer cannot be cast to String.
‚úî Type of error ‚Üí Runtime Exception
‚ö° ClassCastException

Exact exception:

java.lang.ClassCastException: java.lang.Integer cannot be cast to java.lang.String


There Are TWO Meanings of the Word ‚ÄúError‚Äù in Java
1Ô∏è‚É£ ‚ÄúError‚Äù (as in syntax/type error) ‚Üí Compile-time error

This is the general English meaning of the word ‚Äúerror‚Äù.

Examples:

Type mismatch

Syntax mistakes

Missing semicolon

Inconvertible types

These are NOT Java Error objects.
They are compiler faults, not part of Java‚Äôs exception hierarchy.

Example:
int x = 0;
(String) x;


Compiler says:

inconvertible types: int cannot be converted to String


This is a compile-time error, NOT:

not an exception

not a runtime error

not a java.lang.Error

Just a compiler rejection.

üö® 2Ô∏è‚É£ Java ‚ÄúErrors‚Äù (java.lang.Error) ‚Üí Runtime problems

These are actual Java classes and occur only at runtime.

Examples:

OutOfMemoryError

StackOverflowError

AssertionError

VirtualMachineError

These belong to this hierarchy:

Throwable
 ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ Exception
 ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ Error   ‚Üê runtime only


So Java ‚ÄúError‚Äù (the class) always means runtime problems.

| Type                                  | When?          | Meaning                        | Example                |
| ------------------------------------- | -------------- | ------------------------------ | ---------------------- |
| **compile-time error**                | BEFORE running | Code invalid; compiler rejects | `(String) int`         |
| **runtime exception**                 | DURING running | Program threw exception        | `NullPointerException` |
| **runtime error (`java.lang.Error`)** | DURING running | JVM-level failure              | `OutOfMemoryError`     |


1. int x = 0; (String) x; ‚Üí what type?

üëâ Compile-time error (not an exception, not java.lang.Error)

2. Why is this not a runtime Error?

Because JVM never runs this code ‚Äî the compiler blocks it.

3. Are Java Errors always runtime?

üëâ YES ‚Äî only java.lang.Error and its subclasses occur at runtime.
Compiler errors are not Java Errors.